Loan Data Exploration by Oladipupo Shado¶

INTRODUCTION¶

AIM: The goal of this project is to classify and predict whether or not the borrower paid back their loan in full.

Dataset¶

The dataset is obtained from lendingClub.com Lending Club connects people who need money (borrowers) with people who have money (investors). Hopefully, as an investor you would want to invest in people who showed a profile of having a high probability of paying you back. Lending club had a very interesting year in 2016, so let's check out some of their data and keep the context in mind. This data is from the website before they even went public.

Categorical Features¶

Get the data ready for Random Forest Classification Model

In [16]:
#Create a list of 1 element containing the string 'purpose'. Call this list cat_feats
cat_feat = ['purpose']
In [17]:
#use pd.get_dummies(loans,columns=cat_feats,drop_first=True) to create a fixed larger dataframe that has new feature columns with dummy variables. Set this dataframe as final_data.
final_loan =pd.get_dummies(loan,columns=cat_feat,drop_first=True)

Train Test Split¶

In [19]:
#Import Train test split from sklearn.model_selection
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
In [20]:
X= final_loan.drop('not.fully.paid', axis=1)
y= final_loan['not.fully.paid']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split (X, y, test_size=0.33, random_state=100)

Training a Decision Tree Model¶

In [22]:
#Impor Decision tree classifier from sklearn.tree
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
In [23]:
#Create an instance of DecisionTreeClassifier() called dtree and fit it to the training data.
dtrees = DecisionTreeClassifier()
In [24]:
dtrees.fit(X_train,y_train)

Conclusion and Recommendation¶

The random forest classifier performed better than the Decision tree classifier. As a result of this the random forest classifier is a good model for evaluating and predicting whether or not a borrower will pay back their loan in full.
